# Clean Architecture Enforcement

Apply this quality gate to every non-trivial change set.
Use `system-architecture-blueprint.mdc` and `router-service-boundaries.mdc` as canonical architecture rules.

## 1) Drift Sweep (required)

Before finishing, explicitly check for architectural drift in touched flows:

- duplicated business logic across views/services
- router logic that should live in feature services
- ad-hoc UI implementations where a shared component already exists
- expanding monolith files that should be decomposed

## 2) Shared-First Rule

- If a shared abstraction exists (component/hook/service), extend or reuse it first.
- Do not introduce parallel implementations without a documented reason.
- For task list flows, default to the shared TaskBoard pattern unless technically impossible.

## 3) Thin-Boundary Rule

- Enforce thin boundaries per canonical rules; avoid duplicating business logic across transport/UI layers.

## 4) Decomposition Trigger

When a touched file is large and gaining responsibilities, extract focused modules now (not later):

- move pure logic to utilities/services
- move stateful behavior to focused hooks/services
- keep rendering/orchestration boundaries clear

## 5) Completion Gate

In the final note, include:

- what drift was reduced
- what was intentionally not refactored (and why)
- where follow-up decomposition is still recommended
